{"title_page": "Kwame Governs Agbodza", "text_new": "{{short description|Ghanaian politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Kwame Governs Agbodza\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = \n| alt = \n| constituency_MP = [[Adaklu Constituency]]\n| parliament = Ghana\n| majority =\n| predecessor =\n| successor = \n| term_start =\n| term_end =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1973|9|22}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Ghanaian\n| spouse =\n| party = [[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| signature =\n| signature_alt =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Kwame Governs Agbodza''' is a Ghanaian politician and member of the [[MPs elected in the Ghanaian parliamentary election, 2016|Seventh Parliament of the Fourth Republic of Ghana]] representing the Adaklu Constituency in the Volta Region on the ticket of the National Democratic Congress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanamps.com/mps/details.php?id=5374|title=Ghana MPs - List of MPs|website=www.ghanamps.com|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and Education ==\nKwame Governs was born on 22 September 1973 at Adaklu Kordiase in the Volta region of Ghana. He then had his postgraduate Diploma in architecture at University of Westminster, proceeded to have his Diploma in architecture at university of East London. He then returned to Ghana to have his Bachelor of science degree in architecture at kwame Nkrumah University of science and technology . He attended Royal institute of British Architects to attain his chartered architecture certificate and also got another chartered architecture certificate from Ghana institute of Architect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.gh/mps?mp=11|title=Parliament of Ghana|website=www.parliament.gh|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\nKwame Governs is managing director of southworld technical services from 1999 to date, he is the  Chief Executive officer at Architects Co partners from 2010 to date and also Chief Executive Officer at kay and partners from 2012 to date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.gh/mps?mp=11|title=Parliament of Ghana|website=www.parliament.gh|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe is identified as a Christian and he is married with two children .<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanamps.com/mps/details.php?id=2468|title=Ghana MPs - MP Details - Agbodza, Kwame Governs|website=www.ghanamps.com|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\n== Political ==\nKwame Governs won the seat by 11,825 votes out of 13,440 valid cast votes which was equivalent to 87.98%. He was then elected by Parliament to join the Roads and transportation committee and members holding offices of profits committee .<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanamps.com/mps/details.php?id=2468|title=Ghana MPs - MP Details - Agbodza, Kwame Governs|website=www.ghanamps.com|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> \n<br />\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Agbodza, Kwame Governs}}\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 2017\u2013]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:National Democratic Congress (Ghana) politicians]]\n\n\n{{Ghana-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ghanaian politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Kwame Governs Agbodza\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = \n| alt = \n| constituency_MP = [[Adaklu Constituency]]\n| parliament = Ghana\n| majority =\n| predecessor =\n| successor = \n| term_start =\n| term_end =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1973|9|22}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Ghanaian\n| spouse =\n| party = [[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| signature =\n| signature_alt =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Kwame Governs Agbodza''' is a Ghanaian politician and member of the [[MPs elected in the Ghanaian parliamentary election, 2016|Seventh Parliament of the Fourth Republic of Ghana]] representing the Adaklu Constituency in the Volta Region on the ticket of the National Democratic Congress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanamps.com/mps/details.php?id=5374|title=Ghana MPs - List of MPs|website=www.ghanamps.com|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and Education ==\nKwame Governs was born on 22 September 1973 at Adaklu Kordiase in the Volta region of Ghana. He then had his postgraduate Diploma in architecture at University of Westminster , proceeded to have his Diploma in architecture at university of East London. He then returned to Ghana to have his Bachelor of science degree in architecture at kwame Nkrumah University of science and technology . He attended Royal institute of British Architects to attain his chartered architecture certificate and also got another chartered architecture certificate from Ghana institute of Architect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.gh/mps?mp=11|title=Parliament of Ghana|website=www.parliament.gh|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\nKwame Governs is managing director of southworld technical services from 1999 to date, he is the  Chief Executive officer at Architects Co partners from 2010 to date and also Chief Executive Officer at kay and partners from 2012 to date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.gh/mps?mp=11|title=Parliament of Ghana|website=www.parliament.gh|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe is identified as a christian and he is married with two children .<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanamps.com/mps/details.php?id=2468|title=Ghana MPs - MP Details - Agbodza, Kwame Governs|website=www.ghanamps.com|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\n== Political ==\nKwame Governs won the seat by 11,825 votes out of 13,440 valid cast votes which was equivalent to 87.98%. He was then elected by Parliament to join the Roads and transportation committee and members holding offices of profits committee .<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanamps.com/mps/details.php?id=2468|title=Ghana MPs - MP Details - Agbodza, Kwame Governs|website=www.ghanamps.com|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> \n<br />\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Agbodza, Kwame Governs}}\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 2017\u2013]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:National Democratic Congress (Ghana) politicians]]\n\n\n{{Ghana-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: christian \u2192 Christian,  ,  \u2192 ,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kwame_Governs_Agbodza"}
{"title_page": "Johnson Kwaku Adu", "text_new": "{{short description|Ghanaian politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Johnson Kwaku Adu\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = \n| alt = \n| constituency_MP = [[Ahafo Ano South West Constituency]]\n| parliament = Ghana\n| majority =\n| predecessor =\n| successor = \n| term_start =\n| term_end =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1969|8|10}} \n| birth_place =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Ghanaian\n| spouse =\n| party = [[New Patriotic Party]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| signature =\n| signature_alt =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Johnson Kwaku Adu''' (born 10 August 1969) is a Ghanaian politician and member of the [[MPs elected in the Ghanaian parliamentary election, 2016|Seventh Parliament of the Fourth Republic of Ghana]] representing the Ahafo Ano South West Constituency in the [[Ashanti Region]] on the ticket of the New Patriotic Party.<ref name=\"mps24\"/>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nAdu was born on 10 August 1969 in Akrokerri in the Ashanti Region.\n\nHe earned his BEd (Science) at [[University of Education, Winneba]] in 2001.<ref name=\"mps24\"/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAdu is a Christian and fellowships at Church of Pentecost.<ref name=\"mps24\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.gh/mps?mp=24|title=Parliament of Ghana|website=www.parliament.gh|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref> He is married with two children.<ref name=\"mps\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanamps.com/mps/details.php?id=5293|title=Ghana MPs - MP Details - Adu, Johnson Kwaku|website=www.ghanamps.com|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAdu was a NADMO District Coordinator for Ahafo Ano South District from 2002 to 2009, and GES (Circuit Supervisor) Ahafo Ano District Office from 2010 to 2012.<ref name=\"mps\"/> He was also an educationist.<ref name=\"mps\"/>\n\n== Political life ==\nHe was a majority member of the 6th  parliament of the 4th republic of Ghana. He was the Presiding Member of Ahafo Ano South District Assembly, Mankraso, from April 2009 to January 2011; and MP from January 2013 to date; it is his second term.<ref name=\"mps\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adu, Johnson Kwaku}}\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 2017\u2013]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Patriotic Party politicians]]\n\n{{Ghana-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ghanaian politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Johnson Kwaku Adu\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = \n| alt = \n| constituency_MP = [[Ahafo Ano South West Constituency]]\n| parliament = Ghana\n| majority =\n| predecessor =\n| successor = \n| term_start =\n| term_end =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1969|8|10}} \n| birth_place =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Ghanaian\n| spouse =\n| party = [[New Patriotic Party]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| signature =\n| signature_alt =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Johnson Kwaku Adu''' (born 10 August 1969) is a Ghanaian politician and member of the [[MPs elected in the Ghanaian parliamentary election, 2016|Seventh Parliament of the Fourth Republic of Ghana]] representing the Ahafo Ano South West Constituency in the [[Ashanti Region]] on the ticket of the New Patriotic Party.<ref name=\"mps24\"/>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nAdu was born on 10 August 1969 in Akrokerri in the Ashanti Region.\n\nHe earned his BEd (Science) at [[University of Education, Winneba]] in 2001.<ref name=\"mps24\"/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAdu is a Christian and fellowships at Church of Pentecost.<ref name=\"mps24\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.gh/mps?mp=24|title=Parliament of Ghana|website=www.parliament.gh|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref> He is married with two children.<ref name=\"mps\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanamps.com/mps/details.php?id=5293|title=Ghana MPs - MP Details - Adu, Johnson Kwaku|website=www.ghanamps.com|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAdu was a NADMO District Coordinator for Ahafo Ano South District from 2002 to 2009, and GES (Circuit Supervisor) Ahafo Ano Distric Office from 2010 to 2012.<ref name=\"mps\"/> He was also an educationist.<ref name=\"mps\"/>\n\n== Political life ==\nHe was a majority member of the 6th  parliament of the 4th republic of Ghana. He was the Presiding Member of Ahafo Ano South District Assembly, Mankraso, from April 2009 to January 2011; and MP from January 2013 to date; it is his second term.<ref name=\"mps\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adu, Johnson Kwaku}}\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 2017\u2013]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Patriotic Party politicians]]\n\n{{Ghana-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: Distric \u2192 District", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johnson_Kwaku_Adu"}
{"title_page": "Roberto Gaggioli", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Roberto Gaggioli\n| image          = Roberto_winning_philly.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        = Roberto Gaggioli in 1988\n| fullname       =\n| nickname       =\n| birth_date     = {{bda|1962|9|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Vinci, Italy]]\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    = Retired\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| amateurteam1   =\n| amateuryears2  =\n| amateurteam2   =\n| proyears1      = 1985\u20131986\n| proteam1       = {{ct|Alfa Lum|1985}}\n| proyears2      = 1987\u20131988\n| proteam2       = Pepsi-Cola\n| proyears3      = 1989\n| proteam3       = Eurocar\u2013Mosoca\u2013Galli\n| proyears4      = 1990\u20131994\n| proteam4       = Coors Light\n| proyears5      = 1995\n| proteam5       = Guiltless Gourmet\n| proyears6      = 1996\n| proteam6       = Chevrolet\u2013LA Sheriff\n| proyears7      = 1997\n| proteam7       = Plymouth\u2013Elsworth\n| proyears8      = 1998\n| proteam8       = Oilme\u2013Klein\n| proyears9      = 2001\n| proteam9       = DeFeet\u2013LeMond\n| proyears10     = 2002\n| proteam10      = {{ct|AMO|2002}}\n| proyears11     = 2002\n| proteam11      = Schroeder Iron\n| proyears12     = 2004\u20132005\n| proteam12      = Team Monex\n| majorwins      =\n| medaltemplates =\n| show-medals    =\n}}\n'''Roberto Gaggioli''' (born 10 September 1962 in [[Vinci, Tuscany|Vinci]]) is an Italian former cyclist.\n\nProfessional from 1985 to 2005, Gaggioli spent most of his career in the [[United States]]. He won the [[Philadelphia International Championship]] in 1988, and the [[International Cycling Classic]] in 1990 and 1992. He rode in the [[1986 Giro d'Italia]], finishing in 127th position.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/rider.php?id=174529 | title=Roberto Gaggioli | work=ProCyclingStats | accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nHis father Luciano Gaggioli was a professional cyclist from 1960 to 1963. He married [[Lynn Brotzman]], also a professional cyclist.\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1986\n: 1st [[Coppa Bernocchi]]\n;1987\n: 1st [[Fitchburg Longsjo Classic]]\n: 1st Stage 8 [[Coors Classic]]\n: 2nd [[De Kustpijl]]\n;1988\n: 1st [[Philadelphia International Championship]]\n: 1st Stage 3 [[Giro del Trentino]]\n: 1st Overall [[Tour of Somerville]]\n;1990\n: 1st [[International Cycling Classic]]\n;1991\n: 1st Stage 2 [[Cascade Classic]]\n;1992\n: 1st [[International Cycling Classic]]\n: 1st Stages 3 & 12 [[Vuelta a Colombia]]\n;1993\n: 1st [[Reading Classic|New Jersey National Bank Classic]]\n: 1st Stage 2 [[Fitchburg Longsjo Classic]]\n: 1st Stage 1 [[Settimana Ciclistica Lombarda]]\n;1994\n: 1st Stage 4 [[Redlands Bicycle Classic]]\n;1995\n: 1st Stages 1 & 10 [[Herald Sun Tour]]\n: 1st Stage 5 [[Tour de Toona]]\n: 1st Overall [[Valley of the Sun Stage Race]]\n::1st Stage 3\n;1996\n: 1st Stage 1a [[Herald Sun Tour]]\n: 2nd  [[Philadelphia International Championship]]\n;1998\n: 1st Stage 3 [[Tour de Langkawi]]\n;2001\n: 1st Stage 3 [[Tour of Croatia]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gaggioli, Roberto}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Vinci, Tuscany]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1960s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Roberto Gaggioli\n| image          = Roberto_winning_philly.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        = Roberto Gaggioli in 1988\n| fullname       =\n| nickname       =\n| birth_date     = {{bda|1962|9|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Vinci, Italy]]\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    = Retired\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| amateurteam1   =\n| amateuryears2  =\n| amateurteam2   =\n| proyears1