{"title_page": "Kwame Asafu Adjei", "text_new": "{{short description|Ghanaian politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Kwame Asafu Adjei\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = \n| alt = \n| constituency_MP = [[Nsuta-Kwamang-Beposo Constituency]]\n| parliament = Ghana\n| majority =\n| predecessor =\n| successor = \n| term_start =\n| term_end =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1950|10|10}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Ghanaian\n| spouse =\n| party = [[New Patriotic Party]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| signature =\n| signature_alt =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Kwame Asafu Adjei''' is a Ghanaian politician and member of the [[MPs elected in the Ghanaian parliamentary election, 2016|Seventh Parliament of the Fourth Republic of Ghana]], representing the Nsuta-Kwamang-Beposo Constituency in the [[Ashanti Region]] on the ticket of the [[New Patriotic Party]].<ref>https://www.parliament.gh/mps?mp=192</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanamps.com/mps/details.php?id=5354|title=Ghana MPs - MP Details - Asafu-Adjei, Kwame|website=www.ghanamps.com|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life and Education ==\nAdjei was born on  10 October, 1950 in a town called [[Nsuta]] in the Ashanti Region. He acquired a Master of Science degree in Agricultural Economics from  [[Tennessee State University]], [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[United States|USA]] in 1980. He worked as the Chief Executive Officer of Asafaco Consult Company Limited in Accra. He is a Christian and married with three children.<ref name=\":0\" /><br />\n\n== Political Career ==\nHe was elected into the sixth parliament of the 4th republic of Ghana on 7 January, 2013 after he contested in the 2012 Ghanaian General Elections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/election2012/parliament.constituency.php?ID=136&res=pm|title=Parliamentary Results - Nsuta, Kwamang, BeposoConstituency|website=www.ghanaweb.com|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> He was then reelected into the seventh parliament of the fourth republic of Ghana on 7 January, 2017 after obtaining 51.03% of the valid votes cast at the 2016 Ghanaian General Elections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ghanaelections.peacefmonline.com/pages/2016/ashanti/31/|title=NDC Primaries: Nsuta Kwamang Constituency|last=|first=|date=|website=Peace FM Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> \n\n== Personal life ==\nHe is a Christian and married with three children.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 2017\u2013]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adjei, Kwame Asafu}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Patriotic Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Ghana]]\n[[Category:Tennessee State University alumni]]\n\n{{Ghana-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ghanaian politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Kwame Asafu Adjei\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = \n| alt = \n| constituency_MP = [[Nsuta-Kwamang-Beposo Constituency]]\n| parliament = Ghana\n| majority =\n| predecessor =\n| successor = \n| term_start =\n| term_end =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1950|10|10}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Ghanaian\n| spouse =\n| party = [[New Patriotic Party]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| signature =\n| signature_alt =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Kwame Asafu Adjei''' is a Ghanaian politician and member of the [[MPs elected in the Ghanaian parliamentary election, 2016|Seventh Parliament of the Fourth Republic of Ghana]], representing the Nsuta-Kwamang-Beposo Constituency in the [[Ashanti Region]] on the ticket of the [[New Patriotic Party]].<ref>https://www.parliament.gh/mps?mp=192</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanamps.com/mps/details.php?id=5354|title=Ghana MPs - MP Details - Asafu-Adjei, Kwame|website=www.ghanamps.com|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life and Education ==\nAdjei was born on  10 October, 1950 in a town called [[Nsuta]] in the Ashanti Region. He acquired a Master of Science degree in Agricultural Economics from  [[Tennessee State University]], [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[United States|USA]] in 1980. He worked as the Chief Executive Officer of Asafaco Consult Company Limited in Accra. He is a christian and married with three children.<ref name=\":0\" /><br />\n\n== Political Career ==\nHe was elected into the sixth parliament of the 4th republic of Ghana on 7 January, 2013 after he contested in the 2012 Ghanaian General Elections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/election2012/parliament.constituency.php?ID=136&res=pm|title=Parliamentary Results - Nsuta, Kwamang, BeposoConstituency|website=www.ghanaweb.com|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> He was then reelected into the seventh parliament of the fourth republic of Ghana on 7 January, 2017 after obtaining 51.03% of the valid votes cast at the 2016 Ghanaian General Elections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ghanaelections.peacefmonline.com/pages/2016/ashanti/31/|title=NDC Primaries: Nsuta Kwamang Constituency|last=|first=|date=|website=Peace FM Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> \n\n== Personal life ==\nHe is a christian and married with three children.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 2017\u2013]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adjei, Kwame Asafu}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Patriotic Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Ghana]]\n[[Category:Tennessee State University alumni]]\n\n{{Ghana-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: christian \u2192 Christian (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kwame_Asafu_Adjei"}
{"title_page": "Frimpong Yaw Addo", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Frimpong Yaw Addo\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = \n| alt = \n| constituency_MP = [[Manso-Adubia Constituency]]\n| parliament = Ghana\n| majority =\n| predecessor =\n| successor = \n| term_start =\n| term_end =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|9|2}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Ghanaian\n| spouse =\n| party = [[New Patriotic Party]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| signature =\n| signature_alt =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Frimpong Yaw Addo''' is a Ghanaian politician and member of the [[MPs elected in the Ghanaian parliamentary election, 2016|Seventh Parliament of the Fourth Republic of Ghana]] representing the Manso-Adubia Constituency in the [[Ashanti Region]] on the ticket of the New Patriotic Party.<ref>https://www.parliament.gh/mps?mp=166</ref>\n\n== Personal Life and Education ==\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Frimpong Yaw Addo\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = \n| alt = \n| constituency_MP = [[Manso-Adubia Constituency]]\n| parliament = Ghana\n| majority = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| term_start = \n| term_end = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|9|2}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = Ghanaian\n| spouse = \n| party = [[New Patriotic Party]]\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n\nFrimpong Yaw Addo was born on 2nd of September 1962 in a town called Manso Gyeduako in his region. He had his Bachelor of Arts degree in Sociology and Diploma in English from University of Cape Coast. He is a Christian and married with five children.    \n\n== Political Career ==\nHe became the first MP for his constituency after emerging top in the 2012 Ghanaian General Elections. He was then reelected for the second term in the 2016 Ghanaian General Elections where he obtained 69.86% of the total votes cast. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Addo, Frimpong Yaw}}\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 2017\u2013]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:New Patriotic Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{Ghana-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Frimpong Yaw Addo\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = \n| alt = \n| constituency_MP = [[Manso-Adubia Constituency]]\n| parliament = Ghana\n| majority =\n| predecessor =\n| successor = \n| term_start =\n| term_end =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|9|2}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = Ghanaian\n| spouse =\n| party = [[New Patriotic Party]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| signature =\n| signature_alt =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Frimpong Yaw Addo''' is a Ghanaian politician and member of the [[MPs elected in the Ghanaian parliamentary election, 2016|Seventh Parliament of the Fourth Republic of Ghana]] representing the Manso-Adubia Constituency in the [[Ashanti Region]] on the ticket of the New Patriotic Party.<ref>https://www.parliament.gh/mps?mp=166</ref>\n\n== Personal Life and Education ==\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Frimpong Yaw Addo\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = \n| alt = \n| constituency_MP = [[Manso-Adubia Constituency]]\n| parliament = Ghana\n| majority = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| term_start = \n| term_end = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|9|2}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = Ghanaian\n| spouse = \n| party = [[New Patriotic Party]]\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n\nFrimpong Yaw Addo was born on 2nd of September 1962 in a town called Manso Gyeduako in his region. He had his Bachelor of Arts degree in Sociology and Diploma in English from University of Cape Coast. He is a christian and married with five children.    \n\n== Political Career ==\nHe became the first MP for his constituency after emerging top in the 2012 Ghanaian General Elections. He was then reelected for the second term in the 2016 Ghanaian General Elections where he obtained 69.86% of the total votes cast. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Addo, Frimpong Yaw}}\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 2017\u2013]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:New Patriotic Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{Ghana-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal Life and Education:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: christian \u2192 Christian", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frimpong_Yaw_Addo"}
{"title_page": "Ma\u00efmouna Ndoye Seck", "text_new": "{{short description|Senegalese politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific_prefix   = \n | name               = Ma\u00efmouna Ndoye Seck \n | native_name        = <!--The person's name in their own language, if different.-->\n | native_name_lang   = <!--ISO 639-1 code, e.g., \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} in |native_name= instead.-->\n | honorific_suffix   = \n | image              = \n | image_size         = \n | image_upright      = \n | smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n | alt                = \n | caption            = \n | order              = \n | office             = Minister of Air Transport and Airport Facilities Development\n | status             = <!--If this is specified, overrides Incumbent.-->\n | term_start         = September 7, 2017\n | term_end           = \n | president = [[Macky Sall]]\n | primeminister = [[Mahammed Dionne]]\n | alongside          = \n | deputy             = \n | predecessor        = ''Herself (Minister of Air Transport)''\n | successor          = \n | office2             = Minister of Tourism and Air Transport\n | status2             = <!--If this is specified, overrides Incumbent.-->\n | term_start2         = June 22, 2015\n | term_end2           = September 7, 2017\n | president2 = [[Macky Sall]]\n | primeminister2 = [[Mahammed Dionne]]\n | alongside2          = \n | deputy2             = \n | predecessor2        = [[Abdoulaye Diouf Sarr]]\n | successor2          = [[Mame Mbaye Niang]] ''(Minister of Tourism)''<br>''Herself (Minister of Air Transport)''\n | office3             = Minister of Energies and Sustainable Energy Development\n | status3             = <!--If this is specified, overrides Incumbent.-->\n | term_start3         = September 1, 2013\n | term_end3           = June 22, 2015\n | president3 = [[Macky Sall]]\n | primeminister3 = [[Aminata Tour\u00e9]]<br>[[Mahammed Dionne]]\n | alongside3          = \n | deputy3             = \n | predecessor3        = [[Aly Ngouille Ndiaye]]\n | successor3          = [[Thierno Alassane Sall]]\n |birth_date=1962\n |birth_place=[[Dakar]], Senegal\n |nationality=[[Senegal]]ese\n |alma_mater=''[[\u00c9cole Polytechnique de Thi\u00e8s|\u00c9cole Polytechnique, Thi\u00e8s]]''\n |occupation=Mathematician<br>Engineer\n}}\n\n'''Ma\u00efmouna Ndoye Seck''' (born 1962 in [[Dakar]]) is a [[Senegal]]ese politician. An alumnus of the Ecole Polytechnique of Thi\u00e8s, she was the Minister of Energy from 2013 to 2015 and the Minister of Tourism and Air Transport from 2015 to 2017, before she became the Minister of Air Transport and Airport Facilities Development in September 2017.\n\n==Biography==\nSeck was born in 1962 in [[Dakar]] and studied Engineering and Mechanical Engineering/Design<ref name=\"rewmi\">{{cite web |language=fr |author=Christine Mendy |url=http://www.rewmi.com/nouveau-gouvernement-les-7-etoiles-mohamed-dione.html |title=Nouveau gouvernement : Les 7 \u00e9toiles de Mohamed Dione |website=rewmi.com |access-date=April 16, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425151425/http://www.rewmi.com/nouveau-gouvernement-les-7-etoiles-mohamed-dione.html |archive-date=April 25, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> at the ''[[\u00c9cole Polytechnique de Thi\u00e8s]]'' from 1982.<ref name=\"xalima\">{{cite web |language=fr |url=http://xalimasn.com/maimouna-ndoye-premiere-femme-polytechnicienne-du-senegal-une-mathematicienne-decomplexee/ |title=Ma\u00efmouna Ndoye, premi\u00e8re femme polytechnicienne du S\u00e9n\u00e9gal: Une math\u00e9maticienne d\u00e9complex\u00e9e \u00e0 la t\u00eate du minist\u00e8re de l\u2019\u00e9nergie |date=September 3, 2013 |website=xalima.com |access-date=April 16, 2016}}</ref> She was the first woman to graduate from that school. She also earned a [[master's degree]] in [[energy management]] and [[energy economics|economics]].<ref name=\"rewmi\"/>\n\nSeck was the Principal Private Secretary of the Ministry of Energy, and a government advisor.<ref>{{cite web |language=fr|url=http://www.tourmag.com/Senegal-Maimouna-Ndoye-Seck-nommee-ministre-du-Tourisme-et-des-Transports-aeriens_a74806.html |title=Maimouna Ndoye Seck, une polytechnicienne au minist\u00e8re de l\u2019Energie |date=June 30, 2015 |website=tourmag.com |access-date=April 16, 2016}}</ref> In 2013, she joined the [[Tour\u00e9 Government]] as the Minister of Energy, before she became the Minister of Energy and Sustainable Energy Development within the [[First Dionne Government]] in 2014.\n\nSeck has chaired the Electricity Sector Regulatory Committee (CRSE) with the aim of making energy affordable at a lower price.<ref>{{cite web |language=fr |url=http://www.ces.sn/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=165:2013-12-12-10-19-40&catid=3:actualie&Itemid=32 |title=Le Ministre de l\u2019Energie, Mme Maimouna Ndoye Seck, face aux membres du Conseil \u00e9conomique social et environnemental (Cese) |date=December 12, 2013 |publisher=Social and Environmental Economic Council|access-date=April 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing to the 2015 cabinet reshuffle, Seck became Minister of Tourism and Air Transport<ref>{{cite web |language=fr|url=http://seneweb.com/news/Politique/maimouna-ndoye-seck-une-polytechnicienne-au-ministere-de-l-rsquo-energie_n_104813.html |title=S\u00e9n\u00e9gal : Maimouna Ndoye Seck nomm\u00e9e ministre du Tourisme et des Transports a\u00e9riens |date=September 2, 2013|website=seneweb.com |access-date=April 16, 2016}}</ref> with the aim of re-organising a sector in difficulty notably due to the difficulties of [[Senegal Airlines]].<ref>{{cite web |language=fr |author=Khadim Fall|url=http://www.pressafrik.com/Senegal-Airlines-n-a-jamais-atteint-l-objectif-qui-lui-etait-fixe--Maimouna-Ndoye-Seck_a148607.html |title=\" S\u00e9n\u00e9gal Airlines n\u2019a jamais atteint l\u2019objectif qui lui \u00e9tait fix\u00e9 \", Maimouna Ndoye Seck |date=April 15, 2016 |website=pressafrik.com |access-date=April 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seck, Ma\u00efmouna Ndoye}}\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Senegal]]\n[[Category:Tourism ministers]]\n[[Category:Energy ministers]]\n[[Category:Aviation ministers]]\n[[Category:People from Dakar]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{Senegal-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Senegalese politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific_prefix   = \n | name               = Ma\u00efmouna Ndoye Seck \n | native_name        = <!--The person's name in their own language, if different.-->\n | native_name_lang   = <!--ISO 639-1 code, e.g., \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} in |native_name= instead.-->\n | honorific_suffix   = \n | image              = \n | image_size         = \n | image_upright      = \n | smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n | alt                = \n | caption            = \n | order              = \n | office             = Minister of Air Transport and Airport Facilities Development\n | status             = <!--If this is specified, overrides Incumbent.-->\n | term_start         = September 7, 2017\n | term_end           = \n | president = [[Macky Sall]]\n | primeminister = [[Mahammed Dionne]]\n | alongside          = \n | deputy             = \n | predecessor        = ''Herself (Minister of Air Transport)''\n | successor          = \n | office2             = Minister of Tourism and Air Transport\n | status2             = <!--If this is specified, overrides Incumbent.-->\n | term_start2         = June 22, 2015\n | term_end2           = September 7, 2017\n | president2 = [[Macky Sall]]\n | primeminister2 = [[Mahammed Dionne]]\n | alongside2          = \n | deputy2             = \n | predecessor2        = [[Abdoulaye Diouf Sarr]]\n | successor2          = [[Mame Mbaye Niang]] ''(Minister of Tourism)''<br>''Herself (Minister of Air Transport)''\n | office3             = Minister of Energies and Sustainable Energy Development\n | status3             = <!--If this is specified, overrides Incumbent.-->\n | term_start3         = September 1, 2013\n | term_end3           = June 22, 2015\n | president3 = [[Macky Sall]]\n | primeminister3 = [[Aminata Tour\u00e9]]<br>[[Mahammed Dionne]]\n | alongside3          = \n | deputy3             = \n | predecessor3        = [[Aly Ngouille Ndiaye]]\n | successor3          = [[Thierno Alassane Sall]]\n |birth_date=1962\n |birth_place=[[Dakar]], Senegal\n |nationality=[[Senegal]]ese\n |alma_mater=''[[\u00c9cole Polytechnique de Thi\u00e8s|\u00c9cole Polytechnique, Thi\u00e8s]]''\n |occupation=Mathematician<br>Engineer\n}}\n\n'''Ma\u00efmouna Ndoye Seck''' (born 1962 in [[Dakar]]) is a [[Senegal]]ese politician. An alumni of the Ecole Polytechnique of Thi\u00e8s, she was the Minister of Energy from 2013 to 2015 and the Minister of Tourism and Air Transport from 2015 to 2017, before she became the Minister of Air Transport and Airport Facilities Development in September 2017.\n\n==Biography==\nSeck was born in 1962 in [[Dakar]] and studied Engineering and Mechanical Engineering/Design<ref name=\"rewmi\">{{cite web |language=fr |author=Christine Mendy |url=http://www.rewmi.com/nouveau-gouvernement-les-7-etoiles-mohamed-dione.html |title=Nouveau gouvernement : Les 7 \u00e9toiles de Mohamed Dione |website=rewmi.com |access-date=April 16, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425151425/http://www.rewmi.com/nouveau-gouvernement-les-7-etoiles-mohamed-dione.html |archive-date=April 25, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> at the ''[[\u00c9cole Polytechnique de Thi\u00e8s]]'' from 1982.<ref name=\"xalima\">{{cite web |language=fr |url=http://xalimasn.com/maimouna-ndoye-premiere-femme-polytechnicienne-du-senegal-une-mathematicienne-decomplexee/ |title=Ma\u00efmouna Ndoye, premi\u00e8re femme polytechnicienne du S\u00e9n\u00e9gal: Une math\u00e9maticienne d\u00e9complex\u00e9e \u00e0 la t\u00eate du minist\u00e8re de l\u2019\u00e9nergie |date=September 3, 2013 |website=xalima.com |access-date=April 16, 2016}}</ref> She was the first woman to graduate from that school. She also earned a [[master's degree]] in [[energy management]] and [[energy economics|economics]].<ref name=\"rewmi\"/>\n\nSeck was the Principal Private Secretary of the Ministry of Energy, and a government advisor.<ref>{{cite web |language=fr|url=http://www.tourmag.com/Senegal-Maimouna-Ndoye-Seck-nommee-ministre-du-Tourisme-et-des-Transports-aeriens_a74806.html |title=Maimouna Ndoye Seck, une polytechnicienne au minist\u00e8re de l\u2019Energie |date=June 30, 2015 |website=tourmag.com |access-date=April 16, 2016}}</ref> In 2013, she joined the [[Tour\u00e9 Government]] as the Minister of Energy, before she became the Minister of Energy and Sustainable Energy Development within the [[First Dionne Government]] in 2014.\n\nSeck has chaired the Electricity Sector Regulatory Committee (CRSE) with the aim of making energy affordable at a lower price.<ref>{{cite web |language=fr |url=http://www.ces.sn/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=165:2013-12-12-10-19-40&catid=3:actualie&Itemid=32 |title=Le Ministre de l\u2019Energie, Mme Maimouna Ndoye Seck, face aux membres du Conseil \u00e9conomique social et environnemental (Cese) |date=December 12, 2013 |publisher=Social and Environmental Economic Council|access-date=April 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing to the 2015 cabinet reshuffle, Seck became Minister of Tourism and Air Transport<ref>{{cite web |language=fr|url=http://seneweb.com/news/Politique/maimouna-ndoye-seck-une-polytechnicienne-au-ministere-de-l-rsquo-energie_n_104813.html |title=S\u00e9n\u00e9gal : Maimouna Ndoye Seck nomm\u00e9e ministre du Tourisme et des Transports a\u00e9riens |date=September 2, 2013|website=seneweb.com |access-date=April 16, 2016}}</ref> with the aim of re-organising a sector in difficulty notably due to the difficulties of [[Senegal Airlines]].<ref>{{cite web |language=fr |author=Khadim Fall|url=http://www.pressafrik.com/Senegal-Airlines-n-a-jamais-atteint-l-objectif-qui-lui-etait-fixe--Maimouna-Ndoye-Seck_a148607.html |title=\" S\u00e9n\u00e9gal Airlines n\u2019a jamais atteint l\u2019objectif qui lui \u00e9tait fix\u00e9 \", Maimouna Ndoye Seck |date=April 15, 2016 |website=pressafrik.com |access-date=April 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seck, Ma\u00efmouna Ndoye}}\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Senegal]]\n[[Category:Tourism ministers]]\n[[Category:Energy ministers]]\n[[Category:Aviation ministers]]\n[[Category:People from Dakar]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{Senegal-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: An alumni of \u2192 An alumnus of", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma%C3%AFmouna_Ndoye_Seck"}
{"title_page": "Mamadou Boye Bah", "text_new": "'''Mamadou Boye Bah''' (1 April 1930 \u2013 26 May 2009<ref>[https://abailodiallo.wordpress.com/2012/05/28/souvenons-nous-du-doyen-ba-mamadou-28/ Souvenons-nous du Doyen B\u00e2 Mamadou]</ref>) was a [[Guinea]]n political figure and economist and was one of the leading opponents of the presidents [[S\u00e9kou Tour\u00e9]] and [[Lansana Cont\u00e9]].\n\nBah had originally worked in the Tour\u00e9 government in the early 1960s and in the late 1960s worked for the [[World Bank]] in [[Conakry]].\nHowever, in 1969 he was arrested for allegedly conspiring against the president S\u00e9kou Tour\u00e9 and was sent into exile.\n<ref name=\"Dictionary 2005\">{{cite book|author1=O'Toole, Thomas |author2=Baker, Janice E. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kIiHwg3Y5u4C&pg=PA3&dq=Historical+dictionary+of+Guinea+Guinean+Press+Agency#v=snippet&q=Mamadou%20Boye%20Bah&f=false\n|title=Historical Dictionary of Guinea|publisher=Volume 94 of African historical dictionaries, [[Scarecrow Press]]|year=2005|page=15|isbn=0-8108-4634-9}}</ref>\n\nWhen Tour\u00e9 died in 1984, Bah returned to Guinea and formed the ''[[Union for the New Republic (Guinea)|Union for the New Republic]]'' and become active in the opposition against the military backed government of Lansana Cont\u00e9. He was presidential candidate for the UNR in the [[1993 Guinean presidential election|1993 presidential elections]] and promised to pursue economic and educational development. In the end he received 13% of the vote.<ref name=\"Dictionary 2005\"/> In the 1990s his UNR party became affiliated with the [[Renewal and Progress Party]] led by [[Siradiou Diallo]] as they both shared a distrust of General Cont\u00e9's government.<ref name=\"Dictionary 2005\"/> In 2001, approaching the [[2001 Guinean constitutional referendum|constitutional referendum]], Bah formed a coalition party the [[Movement against the Referendum and for a Political Alternative]] (MOMAD) and demanded a boycott of the elections as he believed the process was plagued with corruption and appealed to other nations for assistance.<ref name=\"Dictionary 2005\"/>\n\nIn 2002 his party didn't share the proposal of boycotting the [[2002 Guinean legislative election|legislative elections]], so he quit the UNR and joined the [[Union of Democratic Forces of Guinea]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bah, Mamadou}}\n[[Category:Guinean politicians]]\n[[Category:Guinean economists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Guinean exiles]]\n[[Category:20th-century economists]]\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n\n\n{{Guinea-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Mamadou Boye Bah''' (1 April 1930 \u2013 26 may 2009<ref>[https://abailodiallo.wordpress.com/2012/05/28/souvenons-nous-du-doyen-ba-mamadou-28/ Souvenons-nous du Doyen B\u00e2 Mamadou]</ref>) was a [[Guinea]]n political figure and economist and was one of the leading opponents of the presidents [[S\u00e9kou Tour\u00e9]] and [[Lansana Cont\u00e9]].\n\nBah had originally worked in the Tour\u00e9 government in the early 1960s and in the late 1960s worked for the [[World Bank]] in [[Conakry]].\nHowever, in 1969 he was arrested for allegedly conspiring against the president S\u00e9kou Tour\u00e9 and was sent into exile.\n<ref name=\"Dictionary 2005\">{{cite book|author1=O'Toole, Thomas |author2=Baker, Janice E. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kIiHwg3Y5u4C&pg=PA3&dq=Historical+dictionary+of+Guinea+Guinean+Press+Agency#v=snippet&q=Mamadou%20Boye%20Bah&f=false\n|title=Historical Dictionary of Guinea|publisher=Volume 94 of African historical dictionaries, [[Scarecrow Press]]|year=2005|page=15|isbn=0-8108-4634-9}}</ref>\n\nWhen Tour\u00e9 died in 1984, Bah returned to Guinea and formed the ''[[Union for the New Republic (Guinea)|Union for the New Republic]]'' and become active in the opposition against the military backed government of Lansana Cont\u00e9. He was presidential candidate for the UNR in the [[1993 Guinean presidential election|1993 presidential elections]] and promised to pursue economic and educational development. In the end he received 13% of the vote.<ref name=\"Dictionary 2005\"/> In the 1990s his UNR party became affiliated with the [[Renewal and Progress Party]] led by [[Siradiou Diallo]] as they both shared a distrust of General Cont\u00e9's government.<ref name=\"Dictionary 2005\"/> In 2001, approaching the [[2001 Guinean constitutional referendum|constitutional referendum]], Bah formed a coalition party the [[Movement against the Referendum and for a Political Alternative]] (MOMAD) and demanded a boycott of the elections as he believed the process was plagued with corruption and appealed to other nations for assistance.<ref name=\"Dictionary 2005\"/>\n\nIn 2002 his party didn't share the proposal of boycotting the [[2002 Guinean legislative election|legislative elections]], so he quit the UNR and joined the [[Union of Democratic Forces of Guinea]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bah, Mamadou}}\n[[Category:Guinean politicians]]\n[[Category:Guinean economists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Guinean exiles]]\n[[Category:20th-century economists]]\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n\n\n{{Guinea-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: may 2009\u230a \u2192 May 2009\u230a", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mamadou_Boye_Bah"}
{"title_page": "Mmasekgoa Masire-Mwamba", "text_new": "[[File:Mmasekgoa Masire-Mwamba addressing panellists crop.jpg|thumb|Mmasekgoa Masire-Mwamba (October 2012).]]\n'''Mmasekgoa Masire-Mwamba''' is a Botswana administrator, [[Commonwealth Deputy Secretary-General]] from 2008 to 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acp.int/content/former-deputy-secretary-general-commonwealth-secretariat-ms-mmasekgoa-masire-mwamba-meets-ac |title=Former Deputy Secretary General of the Commonwealth Secretariat Ms. Mmasekgoa Masire-Mwamba meets with ACP Secretary General |website=Acp.int |date=2015-06-04 |accessdate=2016-12-09}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, she came second to [[Patricia Scotland]] from [[Dominica]] in the voting to become [[Commonwealth Secretary-General]], losing by 26 votes to 24.<ref>{{cite web|last=Khunwane |first=Thelma |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201511301767.html |title=Botswana: Masire-Mwamba Puts Up Strong Fight |website=allAfrica.com |date=2015-11-29 |accessdate=2016-12-09}}</ref>\n\nMasire-Mwamba is married to [[Trevor Mwamba]], formerly [[Bishop of Botswana]] and currently Rector of [[St Margaret's Church, Barking|Barking]], [[East London]].<ref>[http://centreforglobalinclusion.org/The-Centre/mmasekgoa-masire-mwamba/ Centre for Global Inclusion \u2014 Mmasekgoa Masire-Mwamba] (Accessed 14 May 2018)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Masire-Mwamba, Mmasekgoa}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:BBC 100 Women]]\n[[Category:Botswana women in politics]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Deputy Secretaries-General]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Botswana-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Mmasekgoa Masire-Mwamba addressing panellists crop.jpg|thumb|Mmasekgoa Masire-Mwamba (october 2012).]]\n'''Mmasekgoa Masire-Mwamba''' is a Botswana administrator, [[Commonwealth Deputy Secretary-General]] from 2008 to 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acp.int/content/former-deputy-secretary-general-commonwealth-secretariat-ms-mmasekgoa-masire-mwamba-meets-ac |title=Former Deputy Secretary General of the Commonwealth Secretariat Ms. Mmasekgoa Masire-Mwamba meets with ACP Secretary General |website=Acp.int |date=2015-06-04 |accessdate=2016-12-09}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, she came second to [[Patricia Scotland]] from [[Dominica]] in the voting to become [[Commonwealth Secretary-General]], losing by 26 votes to 24.<ref>{{cite web|last=Khunwane |first=Thelma |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201511301767.html |title=Botswana: Masire-Mwamba Puts Up Strong Fight |website=allAfrica.com |date=2015-11-29 |accessdate=2016-12-09}}</ref>\n\nMasire-Mwamba is married to [[Trevor Mwamba]], formerly [[Bishop of Botswana]] and currently Rector of [[St Margaret's Church, Barking|Barking]], [[East London]].<ref>[http://centreforglobalinclusion.org/The-Centre/mmasekgoa-masire-mwamba/ Centre for Global Inclusion \u2014 Mmasekgoa Masire-Mwamba] (Accessed 14 May 2018)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Masire-Mwamba, Mmasekgoa}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:BBC 100 Women]]\n[[Category:Botswana women in politics]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Deputy Secretaries-General]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Botswana-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: october \u2192 October", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mmasekgoa_Masire-Mwamba"}
